@gsusmonzon Be careful. I'm doing the same thing, but I was bit by this issue: https://github.com/seejohnrun/ice_cube/issues/261

There has been a commit to ActiveSupport::TimeWithZone in the last couple of days to fix this issue, but for now, the only thing I've been able to do is monkey patch TimeWithZone in my own app. Even if you stick with Ruby Time or DateTime classes, you'll still get bit by this, as none of them currently save the proper time zone when serializing to YAML.

I'm planning to create some tests to highlight this issue and then set about patching the IceCube's YAML dump/load to save the time zone for every instance of DateTime, Time, or TimeWithZone. But I've been pretty swamped this last week and haven't gotten to it yet.

@avit I'd be really hesitant to monkey patch ActiveSupport within IceCube.

I was looking at the IceCube code for `to_yaml` and `from_yaml`, which appears to work with my example above. I can probably replace the monkey patch in my code with custom accessors that call those instead (or possibly just use https://github.com/avit/schedule_attributes with a patch to change the column name to match my database).

I'm still concerned with `DateTime` and `Time` objects, which don't have time zones associated with them. If they are serialized and deserialized on machines with different default time zones, it could cause the same problem. While that might seem like a rare case, it's a nasty bug when it bites you. It's probably not a good idea to require ActiveSupport, but it might be worth converting any DateTime or Time object to a TimeWithZone object when ActiveSupport is present. Not sure where the best place to do that would be - possibly in `TimeUtil.serialize_time`?

